    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                        <date>July 10 1875</date>
                        <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>I hope that you will forgive me for troubling you, but if you are much engaged or not well, pray do not answer me, &amp; I shall understand the reason.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                        <p>I am very curious to learn, owing to some correspondence with Sir J. Paget on contagion, whether fairy rings start from a central point &amp; spread outwards, or whether they commence as rings.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> In this latter case what can the cause be? If they spread outwards, is any thing known of the rate of spreading?</p>
                        <p>Lastly, is it known on what the Mycelium subsists?<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
                        <p>Pray forgive me for being so troublesome, &amp; believe me, with much respect | yours sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
               
               
                
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">For Berkeley’s reply, see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 23, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10062.xml">letter from M. J. Berkeley, 13 July 1875</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 23, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10048.xml">letter from James Paget, 7 July 1875</ref>. See also <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10070.xml">letter to J. S. Burdon Sanderson, 16 July 1875</ref>.</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f3">Mycelium is the vegetative part of a fungus, characterised by fine branching threads or hyphae; in fungi that form rings, the underground hyphae spread in a circular shape, and mushrooms appear above ground at the edge of the circle.</note> 
                </div>
        
